# 🏆 DevClash 2026 — Complete Hackathon Analysis

> **Event**: DevClash 2026 | **Organizer**: DevKraft  
> **Format**: 24-Hour In-Person Hackathon  
> **Venue**: Dr. D.Y. Patil Institute of Technology, Pimpri  
> **Date**: April 18–19, 2026 (10:00 AM → 10:00 AM)  
> **Website**: [devclash.in](https://devclash.in)

---

## 1. 📋 Event Overview

| Attribute | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Duration** | 24 hours (continuous) |
| **Team Size** | 1–5 members |
| **Eligibility** | Open to all — no age, background, or experience restrictions |
| **Tracks** | **Web3** · **Others** (+ Hirex sub-track) |
| **Problem Statements** | Revealed at 10:00 AM on April 18 — you **cannot** choose your own |
| **Tech Stack** | Any language, framework, or platform allowed |
| **AI Tools** | ✅ Permitted (with mandatory disclosure) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Problem statements are given to you — you do NOT pick your own idea.** This is a critical distinction from open-ended hackathons. Your success depends on how well and how fast you solve *their* specific problem.

---

## 2. 🔀 Track Breakdown

### Track A — Web3
- Build decentralized apps, smart contracts, DeFi tools, NFT platforms, or any Web3 solution
- **Must be deployed on the HeLa Blockchain** (this is mandatory, not optional)
- Submissions must *meaningfully* leverage decentralized infrastructure — don't just bolt on a wallet connection

### Track B — Others
- Solve real-world problems using any tech stack
- Domains include: **Dev Tools, Fintech, EdTech, Career Development, Productivity Tools**, and more
- Broader scope → more creative freedom, but you're solving the organizer's problem statement

### ⚠️ Hirex Sub-Track (Inside "Others")

> [!CAUTION]
> **If you win the Hirex sub-track, all intellectual property (IP) of your project is owned by Hirex.** This is explicitly stated in the rulebook. If you care about retaining ownership of your work, **avoid this sub-track** or participate with full awareness of the IP transfer.

- Dedicated problem statements provided by Hirex
- Evaluated separately with its own winners
- All other tracks: IP remains with the team + DevKraft

---

## 3. ⚖️ Judging Criteria — The Most Critical Section

This is where most teams lose. The judging is **ruthlessly functional**:

| Criteria | Weight | What Judges Want |
|---|---|---|
| **Functional Correctness** | **80%** | ✅ Solves the problem *exactly as specified* · ✅ All required features work · ✅ Stable, deterministic execution · ✅ End-to-end flow without manual intervention · ✅ Handles edge cases (invalid/empty/large inputs) · ✅ Correct state handling (especially Web3) |
| **Completeness** | **20%** | ✅ Entire required scope implemented · ✅ No major missing features · ✅ All core flows covered, not just happy path |

> [!WARNING]
> ### What This Means for Your Strategy
> **UI/UX beauty, innovation, and "wow factor" are NOT in the rubric.** This hackathon scores purely on **correctness and completeness**. A polished UI on a half-working solution will lose to an ugly but fully-functional one.
> 
> **Priority order must be:**
> 1. Make it work correctly (end-to-end)
> 2. Handle edge cases
> 3. Cover all required features
> 4. THEN polish UI if time permits

