## 5. 📦 Submission Requirements Checklist

All submissions due **before 10:00 AM on April 19, 2026**. Late = disqualified.

### Required Materials
- [ ] **Project title** + one-line description
- [ ] **Track selection** (Web3 or Others)
- [ ] **GitHub/GitLab repo** — must be public OR grant judge access
- [ ] **Markdown file** covering:
  - All technologies & AI tools used
  - Step-by-step guide to run project on judges' machines
- [ ] **Working demo** — deployed link, video walkthrough (3–5 min), or APK/build
- [ ] **Presentation deck** (PPT/PDF, 5–10 slides) — Problem, Solution, Demo, Future Scope *(submitted post-hackathon)*

### Submission Rules
- ❌ Only **one project** per team
- ❌ All commits must be **timestamped within the hackathon window** — pre-event commits = **disqualification**
- ❌ No working demo = **not evaluated**
- ❌ Must submit through the **official portal only**

> [!CAUTION]
> **Commit timestamps are checked.** Do NOT initialize your repo before 10:00 AM April 18. Create it fresh when the hackathon starts. Even a boilerplate `create-react-app` commit before the window could flag your team.

---

## 6. 🤖 AI Tools Policy

| Rule | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Allowed?** | ✅ Yes — GitHub Copilot, ChatGPT, Claude, Midjourney, etc. |
| **Disclosure** | 🔴 **Mandatory** — must list all AI tools in submission form |
| **Expectations** | Code must be **reviewed, understood, and adapted** — no wholesale copy-paste |
| **Core Idea** | Must originate from the team — AI is a tool, not the architect |
| **Grilling Risk** | Judges **may ask any member to explain AI-generated code** — inability to explain → score penalty |

> [!TIP]
> **Use AI aggressively but understand every line.** The optimal strategy: use AI to generate boilerplate and solve known patterns, but make sure every team member can walk through any part of the codebase. Split the codebase so each person owns and deeply understands their section.

---

## 7. 📜 Key Rules & Gotchas

### Team Rules
- 1–5 members, fixed from registration — **no swaps allowed, ever**
- All members must be physically present the entire time
- Must stay within your registered track

### Project Rules
- All code must be written during the 24-hour window
- Open-source libraries, frameworks, APIs, public datasets are fine (with attribution)
- **No pre-built projects** — not even partial reuse

### Equipment Advisory
Bring these (not mandatory but recommended):
- 🔌 Extension boards / power strips
- 🔗 LAN-to-USB adapter (in case wired internet is needed)
- 💻 Your own laptops and chargers (obviously)

### IP Ownership
- **General tracks**: IP owned by the team + DevKraft (shared)
- **Hirex sub-track winners**: IP owned entirely by Hirex

---

## 8. 🎯 Winning Strategy — Hour-by-Hour Execution Plan

Given the 80% Functional Correctness + 20% Completeness rubric, here's the optimal execution plan:

### Phase 1: Sprint Start (Hours 0–2) ⚡
- **Read the problem statement 3 times.** Underline every requirement.
- Identify ALL features/requirements explicitly mentioned
- Create a checklist of every functional requirement
- Sketch a **System Design Diagram** (you need this for Round 1)
- Set up repo, boilerplate, and dev environment
- Divide work among team members by feature/module

### Phase 2: Core Build (Hours 2–7) 🔨
- Build the **end-to-end happy path first** — input → processing → output must work
- Focus on the primary flow completely before any secondary features
- **Have the System Design Diagram polished by hour 5**
- By Round 1 (hour 7): Demo a working core flow + present your architecture

### Phase 3: Feature Completion (Hours 7–14) 🏗️
- Add remaining required features one by one
- Start adding **edge case handling** (empty inputs, large inputs, invalid data)
- Write the README/Markdown doc as you go (don't leave it for the end)
- By Round 2 (hour 14): All major features working, edge cases handled for core flow

### Phase 4: Hardening & Polish (Hours 14–22) 🛡️
- Focus entirely on **robustness**: error handling, edge cases, state management
- Test every flow — not just happy path. Try to break your own project
- No manual intervention should be needed for the end-to-end flow
- Prepare your demo video or deploy your app
- Start working on the presentation deck

### Phase 5: Final Sprint (Hours 22–24) 🏁
- **Code freeze at hour 22–23** — only bug fixes after this
- Record 3–5 minute video walkthrough if deploying isn't reliable  
- Final testing of all features
- Submit through the portal **before 10:00 AM** — don't wait until the last minute
- Push all final commits
- Round 3 at hour 23: Present your polished, complete solution

---

## 9. 🧠 Critical Strategic Insights

### What Will Win This Hackathon
1. **Solving the exact problem stated** — not a tangential cool idea
2. **All features working correctly** — deterministic, stable, no crashes
3. **Edge case handling** — empty, invalid, large inputs all handled gracefully
4. **End-to-end flow without manual intervention** — judges should be able to run it themselves
5. **Complete scope coverage** — every requirement checked off

### What Will NOT Win This Hackathon
- ❌ Beautiful UI with broken backend logic
- ❌ Novel/innovative approach that doesn't solve the stated problem
- ❌ Impressive tech stack that's half-implemented
- ❌ Great presentation but the demo crashes

### Common Disqualification Risks
| Risk | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| Pre-event commits | Create repo ONLY after 10:00 AM April 18 |
| No working demo | Record a video as backup even if deploying |
| Late submission | Submit by 9:30 AM — leave 30 min buffer |
| Missing AI tool disclosure | List EVERY AI tool used, even for minor tasks |
| Can't explain code | Each member must understand their section deeply |

